# Stack config. Edit in place; read by docker compose automatically.
#
# Hardware target for every choice in this file: RTX 4070 (12GB VRAM) +
# 32GB system RAM (~44GB combined), aiming for 20+ tok/s.
#
# ============================================================================
#  HOW THIS FILE WORKS
# ============================================================================
#  Three sections:
#    1. BUILD   — HARDWARE-SPECIFIC compile params, baked into the llama image.
#                 Read these BEFORE your first build: the wrong CUDA_ARCHITECTURES
#                 produces an image that won't run on your GPU.
#    2. GLOBAL  — infra knobs that are the same for every model. Rarely touched.
#    3. MODEL   — a menu of self-contained blocks. Uncomment EXACTLY ONE.
#
#  Each MODEL block carries the full set of parameters Unsloth recommends for
#  that specific model — HF coordinates, samplers, context size, chat template.
#  Don't mix-and-match knobs across blocks: the recommended values are a matched
#  set, tuned per model. Pick a block, uncomment the whole thing, leave the rest
#  commented.
#
#  After switching blocks:
#    docker compose up -d model-downloader   # fetches the new model if needed
#    docker compose up -d llama claude        # restart with new model + context
#
#  All six models are MoE with 3-4B active params — the architecture that hits
#  20+ tok/s on the 12GB/32GB target by CPU-mapping the experts (--fit on) and
#  keeping only dense attention on the GPU. Dense models of similar quality
#  (Gemma 4 31B, Qwen3.6-27B) are deliberately omitted: they don't fit 12GB VRAM
#  and fall back to slow CPU inference.
# ============================================================================


# ============================================================================
#  BUILD — HARDWARE-SPECIFIC compile params. READ BEFORE YOUR FIRST BUILD.
# ============================================================================
#  Unlike everything else in this file (read at container start), these are
#  compiled INTO the llama image. They must match the machine you build on, and
#  the defaults below target an NVIDIA RTX 4070 (Ada Lovelace). After changing
#  any of them, rebuild the image — `up` alone won't pick them up:
#      docker compose build llama && docker compose up -d llama
#
#  >>> If you have a different GPU, set CUDA_ARCHITECTURES for YOUR card before
#  >>> the first build, or llama-server dies at startup with
#  >>> "no kernel image is available for execution on the device".
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# GPU compute capability of the card you RUN on, written WITHOUT the dot
# (8.9 -> 89). Look yours up at https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-gpus :
#     RTX 50xx (Blackwell) = 120    RTX 40xx (Ada)      = 89
#     RTX 30xx (Ampere)    = 86     RTX 20xx (Turing)   = 75
#     A100                 = 80     H100 (Hopper)       = 90
# Default = 89 (RTX 4070, the machine this repo is tuned for).
CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=89

# --- Untested alternatives (uncomment ONE in place of the line above) --------
# "Safe NVIDIA choice" (UNTESTED here): compile fat binaries for many archs so a
# single image runs on Turing through Blackwell. Bigger binary and a much slower
# build, but portable across mixed/unknown NVIDIA hardware.
# CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=75;80;86;89;120
#
# Apple Silicon (UNTESTED — and NOT supported by the bundled Dockerfile as-is):
# this var does NOT apply. The image is CUDA-only and Docker Desktop on macOS
# can't pass the Metal GPU into a container. Running on an M-series Mac means
# building llama.cpp natively with -DGGML_METAL=ON (no CUDA) and pointing this
# stack at a host-run llama-server — not wired up here. Listed for awareness.

# CUDA toolkit version for the build image. 13.x needs host driver R580+; if
# `nvidia-smi` shows older, set 12.6.0. Must be a real nvidia/cuda image tag.
CUDA_VERSION=13.1.2

# Parallel compile jobs — set to your CPU's logical core count. Too high on a
# RAM-constrained box can OOM the build; lower it if the build gets killed.
BUILD_JOBS=16


# ============================================================================
#  GLOBAL — applies to every model. Rarely change these.
# ============================================================================

# HuggingFace token — only needed for private / gated repos.
# HF_TOKEN=

# Batching (prompt processing throughput; safe across all models below).
LLAMA_BATCH_SIZE=4096
LLAMA_UBATCH_SIZE=1024

# KV cache quantization — q8_0 halves KV memory vs f16 at negligible quality
# cost, which is what makes long contexts fit in 12GB VRAM.
LLAMA_CACHE_TYPE_K=q8_0
LLAMA_CACHE_TYPE_V=q8_0

# Flash attention: required for the q8_0 KV cache above.
LLAMA_FLASH_ATTN=on

# Unload the model from VRAM after this many idle seconds (re-loads on next req).
LLAMA_SLEEP_IDLE_SECONDS=1800

# Claude Code auth token: any non-empty value; llama-server doesn't validate it.
ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN=dummy

# SearXNG search-result noise filter (applied by the mcp-searxng patch). Many
# engines are enabled for redundancy, so a query returns 100+ results; these trim
# what the model sees. Tunable here — change and `docker compose up -d claude`.
#   MAX_RESULTS: keep only the top-N results by relevance score.
#   MIN_SCORE:   drop results below this relevance score (relative, ~0-1.5 range).
SEARXNG_MAX_RESULTS=8
SEARXNG_MIN_SCORE=0.3

# SearXNG signing key (Flask secret_key) — signs preference cookies for the local
# SearXNG instance. NOT a credential to any external service. Leave blank to have
# the container mint a fresh random key on each start (searxng/entrypoint.sh); set
# an explicit value here if you want it stable across restarts.
SEARXNG_SECRET=

# Domains that bypass the Tor pool and exit straight to the internet. Comma- or
# space-separated; a domain also covers its subdomains ("anthropic.com" matches
# "api.anthropic.com"). haproxy routes these to the direct-proxy container and
# everything else through Tor. Leave blank to send ALL traffic through Tor (the
# default). Change and `docker compose up -d haproxy` — no rebuild.
#
# WARNING: direct domains are NOT anonymised — they see your real IP. Only list
# domains where that's intended (e.g. ones that block Tor exits).
#   DIRECT_DOMAINS=anthropic.com, github.com
DIRECT_DOMAINS=


# ============================================================================
#  MODEL — uncomment EXACTLY ONE block below.
# ============================================================================
#  Notes shared by all blocks:
#   - LLAMA_CTX_SIZE must stay >= 100000 (Claude Code's auto-compaction window
#     is derived from it and is silently disabled below 100k). Most blocks use
#     131072 — the largest context all six models support natively, and what the
#     README benchmarks use. The Qwen3.6 block is the exception at 200000 (the
#     context audit showed it's the only model where a bigger window is usable;
#     see BENCHMARKS.md).
#   - KV-cache memory is what grows fastest at long context, NOT weights. It scales
#     linearly with LLAMA_CTX_SIZE. With the global q8_0 cache (~1 byte/elem),
#     the per-model "KV @128K" figure noted in each block is the budget. GLM is
#     the heaviest (no GQA): ~1.2GB per +10k of context. The newer models use
#     GQA / sliding-window / linear attention and cost 5-10x less per token.
#   - --fit on  : CPU-maps the MoE experts, dense attention on GPU. Do NOT add
#                 --n-gpu-layers alongside it; the two conflict and fall back to
#                 CPU. This is what keeps decode fast on 12GB.
#   - --jinja   : applies the model's real chat template (needed for tool calls).
#   - top_k / repeat-penalty are not first-class vars, so they ride in
#     LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS. Single-quote any value containing JSON braces.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------


# ---- [1] GLM-4.7-Flash -----------------------------------------------------
# 30B total / ~3.6B active. Strong general-purpose + agentic. Hybrid reasoner;
# thinking is disabled here to keep responses tight for an agent loop.
# ~18GB weights. No GQA (20 KV heads), so KV is the heaviest of the set:
# KV @128K ~ 15.8GB; weights+KV ~ 33.8GB. Going above ~150k risks exceeding the
# 44GB budget once the other containers are accounted for — keep ctx modest.
# LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/GLM-4.7-Flash-GGUF
# LLAMA_HF_FILE=GLM-4.7-Flash-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf
# LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=131072
# LLAMA_TEMP=1.0
# LLAMA_TOP_P=0.95
# LLAMA_MIN_P=0.01
# LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified --chat-template-kwargs {"enable_thinking":false}'
  

# ---- [2] Qwen3.6-35B-A3B  (ACTIVE) -----------------------------------------
# 35B total / 3B active. Newest Qwen, top-tier general all-rounder. ~20GB
# weights. Hybrid linear+full attention -> tiny KV: KV @128K ~ 1.3GB;
# weights+KV ~ 21GB, large margin (could run the full 256K context). Hybrid
# reasoner; thinking disabled, so these are Unsloth's *non-thinking* sampler
# values (note presence_penalty 1.5). Measured fastest clean decode of the set
# (~43 tok/s) with no tool-call issues, hence the default.
# CTX is 200000 here (not 131072 like the rest): the context audit showed Qwen3.6
# is the ONLY model where a bigger window is a real win — it's within its 256K
# training, fits memory (~21.6GB RAM), and stays fast at depth (~27 tok/s decode
# at 184k). The other blocks stay at 131072 (capped by training, or too slow at
# depth). See BENCHMARKS.md.
LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-GGUF
LLAMA_HF_FILE=Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf
LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=200000
LLAMA_TEMP=0.7
LLAMA_TOP_P=0.8
LLAMA_MIN_P=0.0
LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified --top-k 20 --presence-penalty 1.5 --chat-template-kwargs {"enable_thinking":false}'


# ---- [3] Qwen3-Coder-30B-A3B-Instruct --------------------------------------
# 30B total / 3B active. Coding/agentic specialist with strong tool-calling —
# best fit for code-heavy agent use. ~17.7GB weights. GQA (4 KV heads):
# KV @128K ~ 6.4GB; weights+KV ~ 24GB.
# (The newer Qwen3-Coder-Next is 80B/3B-active: ~46GB at Q4, over the 44GB
#  budget -> spills to SSD -> slow. Excluded on purpose. This one fits.)
# temp is 0.2, NOT Qwen's recommended 0.7: at 0.7 the model often writes a
# natural-language preamble and then omits the opening <tool_call> tag, so
# llama.cpp's parser (llama.cpp issue #20260) misses the call and leaks the raw
# <function=...> XML into the reply as text (~13% of calls at 0.7). Lowering
# temp keeps it on the canonical format — measured 0 leaks in 170 calls at 0.2.
# LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/Qwen3-Coder-30B-A3B-Instruct-GGUF
# LLAMA_HF_FILE=Qwen3-Coder-30B-A3B-Instruct-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf
# LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=131072
# LLAMA_TEMP=0.2
# LLAMA_TOP_P=0.8
# LLAMA_MIN_P=0.0
# LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified --top-k 20 --repeat-penalty 1.05'


# ---- [4] gpt-oss-20b -------------------------------------------------------
# 21B total / 3.6B active, native MXFP4 (the F16 file IS the 4-bit weights,
# ~13.8GB). Sliding-window attention on half the layers -> KV @128K ~ 1.6GB;
# weights+KV ~ 15GB, mostly resident in 12GB VRAM, so this is the FASTEST
# option (40+ tok/s). OpenAI reasoning model; reasoning rides the harmony
# 'analysis' channel and is surfaced separately, so the agent sees clean text.
# top-k is 100, NOT OpenAI's recommended 0 (disabled): with top-k 0 the model
# can occasionally sample a malformed harmony channel token from the low-prob
# tail, which trips llama.cpp's tool-call parser and returns HTTP 500 (the
# family of llama.cpp issues #20650/#20281). Capping top-k prunes that tail —
# measured 0/40 failures at an amplified temp 1.8, vs ~40% with top-k 0. This
# masks the symptom; the underlying parser regression is upstream's to fix.
# LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/gpt-oss-20b-GGUF
# LLAMA_HF_FILE=gpt-oss-20b-F16.gguf
# LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=131072
# LLAMA_TEMP=1.0
# LLAMA_TOP_P=1.0
# LLAMA_MIN_P=0.0
# LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified --top-k 100'


# ---- [5] Gemma 4 26B-A4B-it ------------------------------------------------
# 26B total / 4B active MoE. Google's latest; strong general quality, balances
# speed and accuracy. ~17GB weights. Sliding-window attention on 25 of 30 layers
# -> KV @128K ~ 2.7GB; weights+KV ~ 20GB, large margin. Slightly more active
# params than the others (~18-25 tok/s). Keep repeat penalty off unless looping.
# LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/gemma-4-26B-A4B-it-GGUF
# LLAMA_HF_FILE=gemma-4-26B-A4B-it-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf
# LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=131072
# LLAMA_TEMP=1.0
# LLAMA_TOP_P=0.95
# LLAMA_MIN_P=0.01
# LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified --top-k 64'


# ---- [6] Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B -------------------------------------------
# 30B total / ~3B active MoE on NVIDIA's hybrid nemotron_h architecture: Mamba2
# SSM layers (constant recurrent state, NO growing KV) interleaved with a few
# attention layers. Only the attention layers contribute KV, so KV @128K is tiny
# (~1-2GB). Largest weights of the set (~21.3GB at UD-Q4_K_XL); weights+KV ~ 23GB,
# still comfortable in the 44GB budget. Hybrid reasoner (<think>/</think>).
# NVIDIA publishes two sampler presets: general/reasoning (temp 1.0 / top_p 1.0)
# and tool-calling (temp 0.6 / top_p 0.95). The tool-calling preset is set below
# because Claude Code is a tool-calling agent. top_k / min_p are unspecified by
# NVIDIA, left at neutral defaults. Context maxes at 131072 (128K) for this GGUF.
# LLAMA_HF_REPO=unsloth/Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B-GGUF
# LLAMA_HF_FILE=Nemotron-3-Nano-30B-A3B-UD-Q4_K_XL.gguf
# LLAMA_CTX_SIZE=131072
# LLAMA_TEMP=0.6
# LLAMA_TOP_P=0.95
# LLAMA_MIN_P=0.0
# LLAMA_EXTRA_ARGS='--fit on --jinja --kv-unified'
